prefixes.to.skip.in.table.name.description=In case prefixes to skip are specified as <b>sys_, p_</b> and reverse engineering \
  is being applied over <b>sys_user</b> and <b>p_product</b> tables, their prefixes will not appear in the corresponding entity names, \
  so the resulting names will be <b>User</b> and <b>Product</b> instead of <b>SysUser</b> and <b>PProduct</b>
prefixes.to.skip.in.column.name.description=In case prefixes to skip are specified as <b>d_, t_</b> and reverse engineering \
  is being applied over <b>d_first_name</b> and <b>t_email</b> columns, their prefixes will not appear in the corresponding entity field names, \
  so the resulting names will be <b>firstName</b> and <b>email</b> instead of <b>dFirstName</b> and <b>tEmail</b>
suffixes.to.skip.in.table.name.description=In case suffixes to skip are specified as <b>_sys, _p</b> and reverse engineering \
  is being applied over <b>user_sys</b> and <b>product_p</b> tables, their prefixes will not appear in the corresponding entity names, \
  so the resulting names will be <b>User</b> and <b>Product</b> instead of <b>UserSys</b> and <b>ProductP</b>
suffixes.to.skip.in.column.name.description=In case suffixes to skip are specified as <b>_d, _t</b> and reverse engineering \
  is being applied over <b>first_name_d</b> and <b>email_t</b> columns, their prefixes will not appear in the corresponding entity field names, \
  so the resulting names will be <b>firstName</b> and <b>email</b> instead of <b>firstNameD</b> and <b>emailT</b>
